{"author":{"id":"a0579889c73f3393941f5edd1d834f666696b6986fe624ea0abf4dd0608320c4"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1613424882,"nonce":"pDSJ4HK/cSH3o1JbZA/AI8IEaHA=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc3OTQ1NzYxMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3392#issuecomment-779457612"},"message":"Hi @bernt-matthias \n\nMITGARD needs to be added to bioconda.\n- I will work to get MITGARD added to bioconda and I will ask for support if needed. Just to know, do you have any easy guide (or step-by-step guide) to do that?\n\nA quick look on your github page showed me that you use the ete3 module to download taxonomy. If I remember correctly this is then stored in the home directory. This won't work, i.e. for Galaxy this would need to be configurable. We have a data manager that downloads the taxdump from the NCBI ftp. Could MITGARD be congigured to work on such a taxdump?\n- You are right, the taxonomy downloaded from ete3 module is saved in the home directory. One important thing is that MITGARD did not use the ete3 module directly. It is used by MitoZ, which is one of the assemblers incorporated into MITGARD. MitoZ did not perform so well with RNA-seq data, it was just implemented to help confirm some regions. Another point is that MitoZ is not able to be installed through conda, it needs to be set up manually (or used with Docker or Singularity container). So, this assembler must be a problem for the conda installation.\n    - What should we do about this issue?\n    - I can implement MITGARD with an option to turn on/off the MitoZ software and make it off by default. Then, Galaxy may not allow the user to set this option on. What do you think?\n\nAre there any other databases involved?\n- No, there are no other databases involved.","files":null}]}